<h5>
    Formula 2:
</h5>

<p class = 'equation'>
    $$
    \text{Energy Used} = \text{Power} \cdot \text{Time}
    $$
</p>

<p>
    This formula is a re-organizing of the first formula to emphasize
    a crucial point:
    power is the rate that energy is transferred from one type of energy to another type of energy!
</p>

<ol class="questionList">
    <li class="question" data-answer = '600 Joules'>
        You use a 20 watt light bulb for a time of 30 seconds. How much energy did you use?
        <br>
        <div class = 'formulaSolvingTable'></div>
    </li>
</ol>

<h5>
    Formula 3:
</h5>

<p class = 'equation'>
    $$
    P = IV
    $$
    $$
    \text{Power} = \text{Current} \cdot \text{Voltage}
    $$
</p>

<p>
    This formula gives you the power emitted by an <emph>electric circuit</emph>.
    It isn't a part of this unit, but it is important to know this is another
    completely different formula for power.
</p>
<p>
    In this formula, the unit for Power is still Watts.
    The unit for current is Amps, and the unit for Voltage is Volts.
</p>

